passages.text: 2H25 to Be Another Change of Underwhelming Results - Position for Savvy and Selective Consumer

Key consumption leading indicators do not show a clear picture of an inflection point into 2H25E beyond the seasonal recovery from lapping a tough comparable base from the pre- electoral period in 1H25. Remittances, job creation and real wage mass continued to lose momentum into July while ANTAD (here) reading was also underwhelming. With this in mind, we believe 2H25E will be another chapter of the tale of several Mexicos (here) depicting a more selective, savvy and price/promotion driven consumer with very distinct dynamics among consumer profiles and consumption occasions. Our top sector pick remains OW- rated (TBBB), benefiting from a format gaining consumer share and occupying market white spaces. Among traditional supermarkets, we prefer N- rated Chedraui, which after a rally YTD trades mostly in line with Walnex and is still expected to outperform the latter in 2H, with limited but welcomed gross margin expansion, despite the industry's lack of pricing power. For N- rated FEMSA, our mildest 2H recovery view is due to the convenience format needing stronger economic acceleration to pick up. Still, a potential increase in buyback activity could be a trigger for the stock in the absence of a pick up in SSS. Liverpool's 2H SSS is expected to decelerate, on top of what appears to be a negative contribution from Nordstrom results already in Liverpool's bottom line, while we maintain a \(30\%\) governance discount.

- Expect a milder recovery in 2H25, and no pricing power. Revisiting expectations for the Mexico retail coverage, we now expect a milder recovery in SSS for 2H with average growth of \(3.9\%\) for the traditional food retailers. In the case of FEMSA we expect \(0.7\%\) SSS growth in 2H following \(-1\%\) in 1H while for TBBB we see \(16.5\%\) SSS vs \(15.5\%\) in 1H. We continue to see a lack of pricing power in the industry in general and expect gross margin expansion only for Chedraui, La Comer and FEMSA in 2H which should translate into EBITDA margin expansion at half the pace.

- Macro indicators fail to support a significant inflection. Lingering slowdown in job creation and remittance flows remain the two key macro variables that keep private consumption subdued in our view. As a result of the former, wage mass in Mexico has decelerated over the past 7 months, growing in July only \(+0.7\%\) , its lowest print since April 2021. On the other hand, remittances are expected to continue under pressure (here and here). Finally, the uneven performance of ANTAD segment components echoes our view that only certain buckets of the population are maintaining purchasing power, albeit with clearly a promotional driven behavior.

- There is limited room for upside surprises. Having revised our top-line and EBITDA expectations lower for all retail companies in our coverage, we land \(1 - 2\%\) below consensus on top line for most companies for this and next year, with the exception of TBBB where we are \(3 / 6\%\) above. At the EBITDA level we find further downside and stand \(2 - 4\%\) below consensus for most companies and while consensus for TBBB as per BBG is hard to read given adjustments, we believe our upside on top line is also reflected at EBITDA.

The labor market remains sluggish with avg wages slowing down as well as formal job creation, in our view explained by the lack of investments YTD both from the private and public sector. As a result, Wage mass growth has decelerated throughout the year, with an average growth of \(+4.2\%\) y/y YTD compared to FY24 avg print of \(+6.7\%\) y/y. In fact, the latest print for job creation as of July (once adjusted for the one-off inclusion of digital platform workers, details in chart note below) showed a \(- 2.6\%\) decrease from June's number, representing \(- 25k\) jobs \((- 0.1\%\) y/y).
Figure 6: Real Wage, Formal Job Creation and Real Wage Mass (Excluding Jobs from Digital Platform Workers) growth y/y

Note: On the formal employment front, July saw an extraordinary increase of \(+5.8\%\) y/y. Nevertheless, this number appears distorted, as at the end of June a labor reform, the purpose of which was to include workers in digital platforms (Uber, Rappi and Didi) to the formal employment base, boosted this growth with \(-1.29\) million jobs. When adjusting formal employment to a more comparable base (excluding digital platform workers), formal employment saw a decrease from June's number of \(-25k\) jobs \((-0.1\%\) y/y).

Remittances have acted as a buffer for consumption in Mexico during tough times (here). However, since December 2024 remittances in USD terms have decelerated, averaging a \(- 4.9\%\) y/y decline. This slowdown, along with the lack of FX tailwinds for the rest of the year, pose further risks to consumption throughout the rest of the year. This drop is not just due to fewer Mexicans migrating to the US; our economists (here) highlighted that remittances from non- Mexicans to nationals in Mexico have decreased as well. States with low migration to the US saw remittances inflows rise and then fall, as irregular migrant encounters in Mexico did. As a result, our economists forecast a \(- 10\%\) y/y decline in remittances for FY25, compared to a \(- 6\%\) decline YTD.

Wal- Mart de Mexico (Neutral; Price Target: Ps65.00)

Investment ThesisRecent operational results brought to light some concerns that suggest a less optimistic outlook for 2025 & 2026. Key challenges included unexpectedly flat to negative traffic in Mexico despite margin investments and stronger- than- anticipated expense pressures that have led to a series of misses at the EBITDA level. Consequently, these factors have prompted a downward revision of our EPS forecasts for 2025 and 2026 partly due to lower FCF generation. Despite these near- term challenges, Walnex is poised to continue leading in Mexico's retail market, bolstered by its omnichannel capabilities and strategic geographic coverage. On top of this, resilient cash return to shareholders (dividend yield of \(\sim 4\%\) ) should continue, despite online investments, supported by good FCF generation and an unleveraged balance sheet. Given the short- term weakness but a solid LT strategy coupled with the stock trading at 18x fwd P/E, we rate Walnex Neutral.
Walnex-New vs Old Estimates
FEMSA (Neutral; Price Target: Ps185.00)

We have a Neutral rating on FEMSA as we see risk- reward balanced following a strong re- rating to FEMSA's embedded retail operations, now trading mostly in line with N- rated Walmex, closing a \(30\%\) historical gap. Disciplined capital allocation and non- core divestments have in our view led the holding discount to narrow from \(50\%\) to \(\sim 35\%\) . Thus, we see limited room for additional re- rating, especially at a time when SSS in core Mexico Oxxo operation remain under pressure, underperforming peers. We believe further reduction in the holding discount is likely tied to the distribution of excess cash, which we find unlikely in the short term following the recent extraordinary dividend announcements. Still, we see in Femsa a highly diversified company focused on non- discretionary consumption. And, despite its defensive nature, FEMSA retail operations should print a resilient organic 5y top- line CAGR of \(8\%\) , which includes its DM exposure, and \(9\%\) on EBITDA.
Femsa Consolidated-New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.
Femsa Comercio-New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have a Dec 2026 price target ofPs 185 and US\\$95/ADR. Our SOTP valuation comprises (1) a 10- year DCF of the Comercio Operations (Proximity Latam, Europe, US, Health Operations and Fuel), which accounts for \(68\%\) of our valuation, (2) Femsa's \(47.2\%\) stake in KOF for which we take J.P. Morgan analyst Lucas Ferreira's current fair equity value weighted by Femsa's stake in the company, to which we apply a \(15\%\) non- core asset holding discount, and accounts for \(30\%\) of our valuation, (3) stakes in JVs (mainly Envoy) valued at 1x fwd EV/Sales which makes up \(5\%\) of our valuation.
BBB (Overweight; Price Target: \(\) 35.50\$

3B is Mexico's largest hard discount food retailer and the fastest growing listed retailer in the country, with estimated market share of \(\sim 2\%\) (formal + informal) vs. \(+20\%\) in countries where the concept is more developed. In this context, we see material room (and track record) for growth with a high- return format \((+26\%)\) ROIC in mature stores) - marked by negative working capital needs - that tends to be complementary to the traditional food retail formats. Also, the net cash structure post- IPO should offer good cushion to the growth plans, especially if the company faces stepped- up competition in the segment. Overall, we see in 3B a company that should print a five- year store CAGR of \(18\%\) , with top line printing a \(28\%\) pace and Adj. EBITDA of \(30\%\) (pre- IFRS16), materially above local peers.
TBBB - New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports and J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have a Dec 2026 price target of US\\$35.50 for TBBB shares. We derive our price target using a 15- year DCF of FCFE using a cost of equity of \(12.3\%\) and a perpetuity growth in nominal Mexican pesos of \(5.5\%\)
Chedraui (Neutral; Price Target: Ps169.00)

Chedraui is Mexico's third largest food retailer in terms of sales area and revenues (with MX representing \(47\%\) of consolidated '24 revenues); however, the company's main source of revenue is its US operations ( \(53\%\) of consolidated '24 revenues). The company has consistently outperformed peers and inflation in sales area productivity over the past four years, achieved the strongest ROIC improvement among peers, and demonstrated superior operational efficiency with the shortest working capital cycle and a leading \(60\%\) cash conversion rate to EBITDA in 2024 (highest among peers). Still, as we see risks from an increased slowdown in US consumer dynamics coupled with a slower- than- expected consumption recovery in Mexico, we see limited space for earnings surprises in the short term, warranting a Neutral view mostly on valuation.
Chedraui-New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have a Neutral rating on Chedraui with a December 2026 price target of Ps169/share derived from a 10- year DCF model using a cost of equity of \(10.6\%\) and a perpetuity growth rate of \(5.0\%\) . At our price target, Chedraui would trade at a \(15.8 \times 26 \mathrm{EP} / \mathrm{E}\) multiple and 6.6x EV/EBITDA.
La Comer (Neutral; Price Target: Ps43.00)

We continue to see the company posting strong SSS; however, it is facing the most challenging comps among Mexican food retailers, as its premium formats (City Market and Fresko) continue to enjoy healthy trends while recent openings mature, posing an extra SSS tailwind. However, the pace of openings has historically been volatile and usually below company guidance. Although we see the strong top- line growth being sustained ahead and ongoing improvements in profitability, we believe current valuation is likely reflecting these positives and the potential step up in store opening pace could result in pressure to margins.
La Comer-New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

Our December 2026 price target of Ps43 is derived through a DCF in local currency using a cost of equity of \(12.9\%\) and a perpetuity growth rate of \(5.5\%\) . At our price target, La Comer would be trading at 18.6x 12m forward P/E.
Organization Soriana (Underweight; Price Target: Ps28.00)
We are UW on Soriana, considering lackluster operating performance vs. peers reflected in lower SSS trends vs peers as well as margins at both gross and EBITDA levels.
Soriana-New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have an Underweight rating on Soriana with a Dec- 2026 price target of Ps28/share derived from a 10- year DCF model using a cost of equity of \(12.4\%\) and a perpetuity growth rate of \(4.5\%\) . At our price target, Soriana would trade at a \(14.6 \times 26 \mathrm{EP} / \mathrm{E}\) multiple and 4.3x EV/EBITDA, which is below current levels.
Liverpool (Neutral; Price Target: Ps108.00)

Despite positive industry trends in Mexico, Liverpool is losing market share, growing at \(60\%\) of the industry pace. The company maintains strong e- commerce execution without overspending, preserving its department store value by adjusting its mix. However, it faces challenges similar to US peers, with e- commerce gaining share in key categories. Consequently, Liverpool is expected to grow at a \(5\%\) pace long- term compared to the industry's \(9\%\)

Despite structural challenges, Liverpool could be seen as a potentially compelling value play in Mexico, supported by its resilient cash flows, implying a compelling FCF yield of \(8.5\%\) potentially supporting a dividend yield of \(11\%\)

Governance discount is in place, as visibility on capital allocation is limited with the investment in Nordstrom increasing concerns. With this in mind, we believe shares face a "governance discount" similar to that of Femsa before its streamlining plan, likely preventing a material valuation re- rating from current levels.
Liverpool-New vs Old Estimates
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have a December 2026 price target of Ps108/share. Our PT is derived from a 10- year DCF using a cost of equity of \(13.6\%\) and \(4.0\%\) growth rate in perpetuity. We add a Ps17 value per share related to its \(49.9\%\) stake in Nordstrom. Furthermore, we apply a \(30\%\) discount to the resulting NPV considering capital allocation concerns. Our price target implies a 12m fwd P/E of \(\sim 6.2x\) and EV/EBITDA of \(\sim 4.3x\)
